John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
The Scottish independent schools traditionally provide excellent education. Looking at the latest outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed in 2018, which is only further strengthened by individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already studying in institutions of this kind, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide students and parents with the best possible services.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers, and the position they occupy as citizens of the world.
In an educational sector where it is possible to design and implement customized school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought after subjects.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language they understand, it will get to their head.
But if you speak in his tongue, it will come to his heart.”
This is an important reminder, because we cannot rely solely on English to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s exam results show that students from independent schools across the country have achieved the best results from foreign languages.
68 percent of all students studying a foreign language achieved a higher grade A (results above 85 percent).
Based on data collected from the 74 member schools of SCIS, 72 percent of students received a higher A degree from Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved A.
These results also show that independent schools in Scotland regard foreign languages as essential knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages as chosen subjects have become as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering, and mathematics in both independent and other types of schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Vocational Training Commission found that 17 percent of employers found filling vacant positions to be difficult due to a lack of language knowledge.
From this we can see that language skills are becoming increasingly necessary to enable young people to pursue a successful career.
As more and more workplaces expect knowledge of foreign languages, language skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career you choose, if you have studied a foreign language, you will gain lifelong knowledge that gives you a clear advantage.
Being able to communicate directly with other nationalities automatically gives a competitive advantage to applicants who speak multiple languages.
According to a survey by YouGov, in which 4,000 adults were surveyed in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of the respondents were not well enough in any foreign language to be able to speak to others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10 percent (15 percent) of the respondents.
This is why it is important to focus on language education for children.
Speaking in several languages, especially in the language of developing countries, can be a tool in the hands of children, which, if equipped, can help them to apply for more important jobs as adults.
Every school in Scotland will have different languages.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while many will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese that are expected to be of paramount importance for the UK by 2020.
Whatever your child’s area of interest, you will be able to learn several elective languages at independent schools, and you will be trained by educators who are experts in your field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that prepares and equips them with the skills they will need to succeed, whatever the future may be.
It is not difficult to see that, in the current global business environment, languages are still vital for the future of a country, and education must reflect this.
In fact, knowledge of modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools offer choice, diverse and quality education to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire – this is how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
