This year, a new subject at Harvard University encouraged students to sleep more, fighting against the ever-growing macho culture of caffeine-heated all-night learning.
An academic came to the conclusion that students from the world’s number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care about themselves.
The course, which he believes was the first such training in the U.S., was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard College of Medicine and practises as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
It encouraged the development of the course by giving a lecture earlier on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why do I only now face this as a senior?’”
He said that no one ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised him,” he told Telegraph.
The course, launched for the first time this year, provides students with an overview of how appropriate sleep habits have a fundamental impact on their academic and sports performance, in addition to having a positive impact on their overall well-being.
According to Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard College of Medicine and director of the university’s health service, the university decided to start the course because during the seven-week period, the students were found to be extraordinarily incapacitated.
The one-hour course also includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a college room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to get acquainted with the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by sleeplessness, and why bedtime routine is important.
In another part, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
They present a map of the university area with interactive icons to encourage participants to rethink their daily routine.
“We know that we will not immediately change the behavior of our students.
But we think they have the right to this knowledge – just as they have the right to be aware of the health effects of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture in which it is considered a performance to learn through one night continues to flourish, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students result in more and more problems caused by sleeplessness.
Sufficient and quality sleep is a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even to protect them from obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain to starve and causes a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and biophysics, and last year Harvard was the first to take one of the professor’s courses.
He said that what he heard there opened his eyes and encouraged him to start training at university level.
He hopes that as a next step, graduate students will also be able to participate in a similar degree program before settling in the competitive sphere.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set up a warning for bedtime, an alarm for waking up, and get acquainted with the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electric screens and LED light sources, which can easily distract them from the daily rhythm and make it difficult for them to fall asleep.
