The Global Citizen Festival was first held in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project. The project is run by an international interest group aimed at eradicating poverty by actively involving more people in the fight against poverty.
The concert is free of charge for those (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) who undertake certain tasks or “acts”, such as volunteering, sending an e-mail to a leading politician, a phone call, or any other meaningful activity to draw attention to the purpose of the project: eradicating poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen been in achieving its goals in the last 12 years?
Is it really an effective way to reward people with a concert ticket to convince others of the importance of action, or is it just another form of so-called “clicktivism” when people feel that they have made a meaningful contribution to a case by signing an online petition or writing a tweet?
Since 2011, according to the data of the Global Citizen, more than 19 million “acts” have been carried out by the project’s supporters, which have served many different purposes.
According to the organization, these actions have contributed to the separation of world leaders from poverty policies and commitments of $37 billion that could impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
