Pelosi spoke in an interview at the Texas Tribune Festival in Austin, Texas.
“I thought unwittingly that if a woman behaved in this way at any time, I would call her ‘hysterical’,” Pelosi explained in his response to Kavanaugh’s testimony before the Justice Committee of the Senate on Thursday.
Kavanaugh, heated with emotion, protested the rumors that he sexually harassed Dr. Christine Blasey Ford in their teenage years.
In his opening speech, Kavanaugh was very emotional, sometimes almost shouting, and his voice closed when he talked about his family and his high school years.
He also explicitly condemned the committee’s democrats, calling the accusations against him “a grotesque and coordinated character assassination,” organized by angry liberals due to Hillary Clinton’s defeat in the 2016 presidential election.
Pelosi said that Kavanaugh’s behavior proved that he was unfit to work in the Supreme Court because he showed that he was biased against the Democrats.
“I think he has excluded himself from his statements and the behavior he has shown against the Clintons and Democrats,” he said.
Pelosi hesitated when asked if he would try to hold Kavanaugh accountable if he was in the position and if the Democrats got the majority in the House of Representatives.
“All I’m saying is that if you don’t tell the truth to Congress or the FBI, it’s not just for the Supreme Court, but also for the court you’re in right now,” Pelosi said.
Kavanaugh is currently a judge in the Court of Appeal of the capital.
Pelosi added that as a Democrat, he is concerned about Kavanaugh’s possible decisions regarding the Affordable Care Act or the Roe vs. Wade case, as Kavanaugh is a conservative judge.
During Kavanaugh’s hearings, he avoided questions about whether he would alter the Supreme Court’s rulings.
“It is not the time for a hysterical, biased person to be among the members of the court and expect us to burst into joy,” Pelosi said.
