How can the U.S.-China trade war be good for Beijing?
The opening of the trade war between the US and China was almost deafening, and while the battle was not yet nearly over, experts say the break between the two countries could benefit Beijing in the long run.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, fired the first warnings early this year by imposing a tax on the most important Chinese export products, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week, as the new tariffs already affect a product worth $200 billion, effectively taxing half of the goods from China to the US.
Beijing has always cut back tariffs on US goods worth $60 billion, most recently between 5% and 10%.
China has vowed to fight back every time, and the world’s second-largest economy will certainly not back down in the near future.
If you wanted to get Washington to back down, that would mean you'd have to give up your waist in front of the demands, but public bowing to the US would be too embarrassing for Xi Chin-ping, China's president.
However, according to experts, if Beijing is good at tactics, the US trade war pressure could be good for China in the long run as it reduces dependence between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick decision can create conditions that can drive any of the economies of the two countries into an economic whirlwind is far more serious than previously acknowledged by observers,” said Abigail Grace, an Asian research assistant at the New American Security think tank.
Syria ‘ready’ to return refugees, foreign minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help in rebuilding the country that was destroyed in the war for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Valid Moallem said that the state of the country is improving.
“The current situation is more stable and safer thanks to the achievements in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to re-establish the integrity of areas destroyed by terrorists, restoring normal conditions.
Now there are all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, who had to flee between terrorism and the self-imposed economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Another six million people in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Moallem said the Syrian state would welcome any help to rebuild the country.
But he stressed that there was no acceptance of conditional assistance or assistance from countries that supported the uprising.
