Red tide news: Decreased concentration in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission’s latest report shows a general reduction in redfish concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the area of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties has been reported to have a more spotty bloom, suggesting a decrease in concentration.
The length of the red tide is about 130 miles, from the northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
About 10 miles from the outskirts of Hillsborough County, there are spots, but compared to last week, in a relatively smaller area.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and along its coasts, low- and high-value concentrations were reported along the coasts of Hillsborough County, from background to high-value concentrations in Manatee County, from background to high-value concentrations in Sarasota County and along its coasts, from background to medium-value concentrations in Charlotte County, from background to high-value concentrations in Lee County and along its coast.
Reports of respiratory irritation have continued in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There were no respiratory irritations reported last week from northwest Florida.
